.book.v1.45O77oSxDMyWsz4Zj0Lxmw"},"creator":{"__ref":"User:4086118"},"recommendFor":null,"updatedAt":1628463658298,"createdAt":1464719203000,"spoilerStatus":false,"lastRevisionAt":1466353992000,"text":"A worthy finish to my reading adventures with Haruf's six novels about rural life in Colorado. Here we get a vision of the tragic life of Edith as the daughter of a selfish, stubborn, and mean spirited farmer in the high and dry plains of eastern Colorado. It is told from the perspective of Roscoe, a neighbor friend who also grew up in this hardscrabble life of farming and whose father once loved the warm and tough Edith. But a terrible accident makes Edith's father forever dependent on her help, which became even more necessary when her beloved but mentally challenged brother makes an escape to travel the U.S., with only postcards to mark his existence over the decades. Roscoe, despite being reviled by Edith's father for being part Indian, finds a way to connect with Edith during the long passage of time, finding much courage in her steadfast sacrifice of her life for the \"ties that bind\". Now he has a chance to help her, which we learn at the beginning of the book has something to do with Edith in her 80s being a suspect in the suspicious death of her father. A dark tale for sure, but one that heralds the grace and bravery of certain folk who survived the tough realities of farming life on the Great Plains.","rating":4,"shelving":{"__typename":"Shelving","shelf":{"__typename":"Shelf","name":"read","webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/4086118?shelf=read"},"taggings":[{"__typename":"Tagging","tag":{"__typename":"Tag","name":"child-abuse","webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/4086118?shelf=child-abuse"}}],"webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1654340902"},"likeCount":51,"viewerHasLiked":null,"commentCount":7,"viewerCanComment({\"resourceType\":\"review\"})":null},"User:632247":{"id":632247,"__typename":"User","legacyId":632247,"imageUrl